                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <ab type="script">Mediocre and irregular</ab>
                        <seg type="ink">Black, red (vivid red, vivid vermillion, strong vermillion).</seg>The handwriting is similar, but not identical to that of AP-008 and AP-064.<date>Late 17th-18th century</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ምዕ፡</abbr> for
                                                  <expan>ምዕራፍ፡ </expan> (e.g., fols. 87va, 88va, 92vb, 83vb)</item>
                           <item>
                              <abbr>ም፡</abbr> for
                                                  <expan>ምዕራፍ፡ </expan> (e.g., fols. 82vb)</item>
                        </list>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">It is difficult to determine whether one or more scribes were involved in writing. The handwriting changes from usually mediocre and irregular to careful and neat (e.g., fols. 7v/8r, 63rv, 100v/101r). Irregularities are e.g., <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
- size of letters significantly differs, also within one column (cp., fols. 32vab, 82ra against 82vb);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic">
- space between letters significantly differs (cp., fols. 9vb against 10ra, 75v against 76r, 99vb);<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic">
- occasionally the ruling was disregarded: text is written between lines, last ruling line is not used (cp., fols. 12ra-17vb).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic">
However, a few distinctive features appear, though not quite regularly throughout the entire Ms.:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic">
- ancient form of 'one' (፩, triangular upwards-oriented)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h8" script="Ethiopic">
- ancient form of 'six' (፮, looking like "compressed" number 'seven') <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h9" script="Ethiopic">
- occasionally short hairlines extending horizontal elements of some letters (e.g. fol. 8ra: ሔ, ን እ, ይ, ደ, ገ)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h10" script="Ethiopic">
- the right loop of ሠ (in all vowel orders) is of smaller size.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
